    <h2>Karlie Kloss uses super coding powers to embrace women in computer science industry</h2>
     <h3> Feminism </h3>
    <p> Karlie Kloss is definitely not your average supermodel. Making the covers of numerous magazines such as Vogue, Bazaar, Glamour, Elle, including many more, Kloss has another superpower; computer coding.  </p>
	<p>Founded in 2015, Kloss began her adventure into computer science and decided to share her new found love of coding with young women all across the U.S. by creating a two-week summer camp for girls 13-18 years old, called "Kode With Klossy." Their mission is to "empower girls to learn to code and become leaders in tech." <p/>
<p>	 A current and ongoing epidemic in the tech industry is the lack of women within the STEM field. Women have been influenced to veer away from the STEM industry as a result of sexual harassment in the workplace. Feminists across the world have taken a stand for women's equality, including Kloss! 
<p>  "Kode With Klossy," is a safe environment for young women to embrace their femininity and love of learning while motivating them to continue a career in the STEM industry; to bring awareness and fight against anti-feminism within the work environment of any STEM field, especially computer science. So, Thank You, Karlie. Your superpower will never go unappreciated. 
</p>
