    <h2>Wisconsin schools brace for next mass shooting with gun shot detection technology</h2>
     <h3> Gun Control </h3>
    <p> Schools in Milwaukee, Wisconsin brace for a possible next mass shooting by implementing gunshot detection technology that will immediately notify police with the hopes that first responders will be able to respond quickly when there is an active shooter. Better to be safe than sorry, right?   </p>
<p> After the recent shooting in Parkland, Florida, Wisconsin lawmakers have approved grants to schools across the state to improve upon security measures as the upcoming school year approaches. The approved grants have provided funding to upgrade cameras and intercom systems as well as putting protective film on windows so they won't shatter.
<p> President Trump has expressed his own opinions, suggesting schools should focus their resources on mental health and behavioral intervention support by providing training for staff in order to evaluate threats and make it easy for students to report suspicious activity. But the overall objective of the gunshot detection technology is to get their local law enforcement to the schools as fast as possible.</p>
